messages.content:
=== MOONSHINER TASK BOUNDARY ===

The image tool I maintain tracks which 4 KiB blocks of a fixed-extent volume image are in use, and the ad-hoc byte-per-block array we use today wastes memory and is slow to scan. I want a proper bitmap library: bitvec.h and bitvec.c, C17, stdint.h/stddef.h only, no allocation anywhere -- the caller owns the word storage, the library only ever touches those words.

Exact surface (the tool and its fsck both build against this):

    #define BV_WORDS(nbits) (((nbits) + 63u) / 64u)

    typedef struct {
        uint64_t *words;   /* caller storage, BV_WORDS(nbits) elements */
        size_t    nbits;
    } bitvec;

    int    bv_init(bitvec *bv, uint64_t *words, size_t nbits);
    int    bv_set(bitvec *bv, size_t i);
    int    bv_clear(bitvec *bv, size_t i);
    int    bv_flip(bitvec *bv, size_t i);
    int    bv_test(const bitvec *bv, size_t i);
    int    bv_set_range(bitvec *bv, size_t lo, size_t hi);
    int    bv_clear_range(bitvec *bv, size_t lo, size_t hi);
    size_t bv_count(const bitvec *bv);
    long   bv_count_range(const bitvec *bv, size_t lo, size_t hi);
    long   bv_next_set(const bitvec *bv, size_t from);
    long   bv_next_clear(const bitvec *bv, size_t from);

Rules, learned the hard way from the fsck:

- bv_init: -1 when bv or words is NULL or nbits is 0; otherwise zero all BV_WORDS(nbits) words (the caller's array is usually stack garbage) and return 0.
- Single-bit ops take a block index. Out of range (i >= nbits) returns -1 and must not touch anything. bv_test returns 0 or 1 (or -1 out of range); set/clear/flip return 0 on success. Bit 0 is the least significant bit of words[0], bit 64 the LSB of words[1], and so on.
- Ranges are half-open [lo, hi). STRICT bounds: lo <= hi <= nbits or the call returns -1 having changed nothing -- never silently clamp; the fsck feeds untrusted extents and needs the error. lo == hi is a valid no-op returning 0. Ranges must handle any alignment: inside one word, exactly on word seams, straddling several words.
- bv_count is a popcount of the map. bv_count_range counts inside [lo, hi) with the same strict bounds, -1 on a bad range.
- bv_next_set / bv_next_clear return the smallest index >= from whose bit is set / clear, or -1 when there is none (from >= nbits is also -1). This is the hot path when the allocator looks for a free block, so skipping whole zero (or full) words rather than testing bit by bit is the point of the exercise -- but only the results are graded.
- Bits at positions >= nbits in the last word must NEVER be set, no matter what combination of range ops runs; bv_count and the scanners must stay exact for maps whose size is not a multiple of 64.
- No globals, no statics, no I/O.

`make test` is the acceptance gate; Makefile, mintest.h and test_bitvec.c are fixed.

messages.reasoning_content:
The task is clear: implement bitvec.h and bitvec.c. The tests are fixed, the Makefile builds test_bitvec.c + bitvec.c with -std=c17 -Wall -Wextra -Werror.

Design:

bitvec.h:
```c
#ifndef BITVEC_H
#define BITVEC_H

#include <stdint.h>
#include <stddef.h>

#define BV_WORDS(nbits) (((nbits) + 63u) / 64u)

typedef struct {
    uint64_t *words;
    size_t    nbits;
} bitvec;

int    bv_init(bitvec *bv, uint64_t *words, size_t nbits);
int    bv_set(bitvec *bv, size_t i);
int    bv_clear(bitvec *bv, size_t i);
int    bv_flip(bitvec *bv, size_t i);
int    bv_test(const bitvec *bv, size_t i);
int    bv_set_range(bitvec *bv, size_t lo, size_t hi);
int    bv_clear_range(bitvec *bv, size_t lo, size_t hi);
size_t bv_count(const bitvec *bv);
long   bv_count_range(const bitvec *bv, size_t lo, size_t hi);
long   bv_next_set(const bitvec *bv, size_t from);
long   bv_next_clear(const bitvec *bv, size_t from);

#endif
```

bitvec.c:

Key details:
- Bit i lives at words[i/64], bit i%64, LSB-first.
- bv_init: validate, zero all words.
- Single-bit ops: bounds check i >= nbits → -1 without touching.
- Range ops: strict validation lo <= hi <= nbits, -1 and change nothing otherwise. lo == hi → 0 no-op.
- Range implementation with masks:
  - first word = lo/64, last word = (hi-1)/64.
  - For the first word: mask of bits from lo%64 to end of word: `~0ull << (lo % 64)`.
  - For the last word: mask of bits 0..(hi-1)%64: careful — hi%64 == 0 means full word. Mask for bits below hi: `hi % 64 == 0 ? ~0ull : ((1ull << (hi % 64)) - 1)`. Avoid shift by 64.
  - If first == last word, combine masks.
- bv_count: popcount over all words; since tail bits are guaranteed never set, a plain popcount over all BV_WORDS words is exact. Use portable popcount (no intrinsics since we should stay portable; __builtin_popcountll is GCC-specific but the Makefile uses gcc... but the contract says stdint.h/stddef.h only — that refers to headers, not builtins. Still, a portable popcount is fine and safe; or use __builtin_popcountll guarded. Simpler: write a small portable popcount using the SWAR technique. Performance is only graded on results, not speed, but word-skipping is requested for the scanners anyway.)
- bv_count_range: validate, then count. Can count word-by-word with masks, or simpler: iterate over the range using the same first/last word mask approach.
- bv_next_set(from): if from >= nbits → -1. Start at word w = from/64, mask off bits below from%64: `word & (~0ull << (from%64))`. If nonzero, answer = w*64 + ctz. Else scan subsequent words for nonzero, skipping zeros. Since tail bits are never set, the found index is always < nbits. Return as long.
- bv_next_clear(from): if from >= nbits → -1. Similar but with complemented words; must mask the tail of the last word so bits >= nbits don't count as "clear". Approach: for the last word, use `~word & tailmask` where tailmask covers valid bits only. Simpler: iterate words; candidate = ~words[w]; mask off bits below from%64 in first word; if w is the last word, mask candidate with the valid-bits mask of the last word. If candidate nonzero → index = w*64 + ctz; since masked, index < nbits. Otherwise continue.

ctz: number of trailing zeros — implement portably: loop or de Bruijn. A simple loop is fine, but a branch-free de Bruijn is nicer. Since only results are graded, use a simple loop over set bits: `while (!(x & 1)) { x >>= 1; n++; }`. That's at most 63 iterations — fine. Actually let me write a small helper `lowest_set_index(uint64_t w)` using the standard popcount of (w & -w) - 1... or just a loop. Keep it simple and correct.

Edge cases to be careful about:
1. Shifts by 64 are UB — must guard everywhere.
2. bv_next_set when from >= nbits → -1. Also nbits could be such that from is within the last partial word — tail bits guaranteed clear so scanning works.
3. bv_next_clear in the last word must not report bits >= nbits. Mask properly.
4. bv_count_range returning long; counts up to nbits which fits in size_t; cast to long. Tests use small values, fine. Note: if nbits > LONG_MAX there'd be overflow, but that's an inherent API limitation; don't worry.
5. bv_set_range with lo == hi → return 0 without touching (validation first: lo <= hi <= nbits, so lo==hi==nbits is fine → 0).
6. bv_init must zero BV_WORDS(nbits) words.

Range mask helper: I'll write a static helper:

```c
/* mask of bits [lo, hi) within a single 64-bit word; lo <= hi, hi <= 64 */
static uint64_t range_mask(unsigned lo, unsigned hi) {
    if (lo == hi) return 0;
    uint64_t top = (hi == 64) ? ~0ull : ((1ull << hi) - 1ull);
    return top & (~0ull << lo);
}
```

Then set_range:
```c
size_t w0 = lo / 64, w1 = (hi - 1) / 64; // only when lo < hi
if (w0 == w1) {
    words[w0] op= range_mask(lo % 64, lo % 64 + (hi - lo));
} else {
    words[w0] op= range_mask(lo % 64, 64);
    for (w = w0 + 1; w < w1; w++) words[w] op= ~0;
    words[w1] op= range_mask(0, hi % 64 == 0 ? 64 : hi % 64);
}
```

Actually hi % 64 for the last word: if hi % 64 == 0, then w1 = (hi-1)/64 and the bits to affect in w1 are all 64 bits → range_mask(0, 64). If hi % 64 != 0, bits 0..hi%64-1 → range_mask(0, hi%64). So `range_mask(0, (hi - 1) % 64 + 1)` handles both: hi%64==0 → (hi-1)%64 = 63 → +1 = 64 → full mask. Nice: `unsigned endbit = (unsigned)((hi - 1) % 64) + 1;`

Similarly for same-word case: endbit relative = lo%64 + (hi-lo) = (hi-1)%64 + 1 when w0 == w1. So uniformly: startbit = lo % 64; endbit = (hi - 1) % 64 + 1. For w0: mask from startbit to (w0==w1 ? endbit : 64). For w1: mask 0 to endbit.

To share code between set and clear, I could write a static helper `apply_range(bitvec*, lo, hi, int set)` or use a function pointer... Keep it simple: write a helper that computes and applies with a flag:

```c
static void range_op(uint64_t *words, size_t lo, size_t hi, int set) {
    size_t w0 = lo / 64;
    size_t w1 = (hi - 1) / 64;
    unsigned startbit = (unsigned)(lo % 64);
    unsigned endbit = (unsigned)((hi - 1) % 64) + 1u;
    if (w0 == w1) {
        uint64_t m = range_mask(startbit, endbit);
        if (set) words[w0] |= m; else words[w0] &= ~m;
        return;
    }
    uint64_t m0 = range_mask(startbit, 64);
    uint64_t m1 = range_mask(0, endbit);
    if (set) {
        words[w0] |= m0;
        for (size_t w = w0 + 1; w < w1; w++) words[w] = ~0ull;
        words[w1] |= m1;
    } else {
        words[w0] &= ~m0;
        for (size_t w = w0 + 1; w < w1; w++) words[w] = 0;
        words[w1] &= ~m1;
    }
}
```

Validation happens in the public functions before calling this, so tail bits beyond nbits: since hi <= nbits, endbit never exceeds nbits - w1*64, so tail bits are never touched. Good.

bv_count: popcount each word. Since tail bits never set, no masking needed. Portable popcount:

```c
static size_t popcount64(uint64_t x) {
    x = x - ((x >> 1) & 0x5555555555555555ull);
    x = (x & 0x3333333333333333ull) + ((x >> 2) & 0x3333333333333333ull);
    x = (x + (x >> 4)) & 0x0F0F0F0F0F0F0F0Full;
    return (size_t)((x * 0x0101010101010101ull) >> 56);
}
```

bv_count_range: validate (lo <= hi <= nbits else -1). If lo == hi return 0. Compute:
```c
size_t w0 = lo / 64, w1 = (hi - 1) / 64;
unsigned startbit = lo % 64, endbit = (hi-1)%64 + 1;
size_t total = 0;
if (w0 == w1) total = popcount64(words[w0] & range_mask(startbit, endbit));
else {
    total += popcount64(words[w0] & range_mask(startbit, 64));
    for (w0+1..w1-1) total += popcount64(words[w]);
    total += popcount64(words[w1] & range_mask(0, endbit));
}
return (long)total;
```

bv_next_set:
```c
if (from >= bv->nbits) return -1;
size_t nwords = BV_WORDS(bv->nbits); // or (nbits + 63) / 64
size_t w = from / 64;
uint64_t cur = bv->words[w] & (~0ull << (from % 64));
for (;;) {
    if (cur) return (long)(w * 64 + ctz64(cur));
    if (++w >= nwords) return -1;
    cur = bv->words[w];
}
```
Tail bits are never set, so any found bit is < nbits. Good.

bv_next_clear:
```c
if (from >= bv->nbits) return -1;
size_t nwords = BV_WORDS(bv->nbits);
size_t w = from / 64;
uint64_t cur = ~bv->words[w] & (~0ull << (from % 64));
/* mask off bits beyond nbits if this is the last word */
unsigned rem = nbits % 64; // valid bits in last word
...
```

Handle the last-word masking: define valid-mask for word w: for w == nwords-1 and nbits%64 != 0, mask = (1ull << (nbits%64)) - 1, else ~0. Apply to cur each iteration (cheap to just compute inside loop, or check at the end). Simple approach:

```c
for (;;) {
    uint64_t valid = ~0ull;
    if (w == nwords - 1 && (bv->nbits % 64) != 0)
        valid = (1ull << (bv->nbits % 64)) - 1ull;
    uint64_t cur = ~bv->words[w] & valid;
    if (w == from / 64) cur &= ~0ull << (from % 64);
    if (cur) return (long)(w * 64 + ctz64(cur));
    if (++w >= nwords) return -1;
}
```

Cleaner to compute the first-word mask before the loop:

```c
long bv_next_clear(const bitvec *bv, size_t from) {
    if (from >= bv->nbits) return -1;
    size_t nwords = BV_WORDS(bv->nbits);
    size_t w = from / 64;
    uint64_t cur = ~bv->words[w] & (~0ull << (from % 64));
    for (;;) {
        if (w == nwords - 1 && (bv->nbits % 64u) != 0)
            cur &= (1ull << (bv->nbits % 64u)) - 1ull;
        if (cur != 0)
            return (long)(w * 64u + ctz64(cur));
        if (++w >= nwords)
            return -1;
        cur = ~bv->words[w];
    }
}
```

This works: first iteration cur already masked below from; then masked to valid bits in the last word. The found ctz is < nbits because of the valid mask. 

ctz64 helper:
```c
static unsigned ctz64(uint64_t x) {
    /* x != 0 */
    unsigned n = 0;
    while ((x & 1ull) == 0) { x >>= 1; n++; }
    return n;
}
```
Or use popcount64((x & (~x + 1)) - 1)... the loop is fine, max 63 iterations on the hot path after skipping whole words — acceptable. Actually, a nicer branchless way: `popcount64((x & (0 - x)) - 1)`. The isolated lowest bit minus one has popcount = index of that bit. That's neat and reuses popcount64. `x & -x` for unsigned: `x & (~x + 1ull)`. Fine, I'll use that.

Wait — one subtlety about bv_next_set masking: `~0ull << (from % 64)` — from%64 is in [0,63], shift OK.

BV_WORDS macro: `(((nbits) + 63u) / 64u)` — with size_t nbits, `nbits + 63u` — 63u is unsigned int, promoted to size_t. Fine.

Header: include stdint.h and stddef.h. Guard.

Also `bv_test` returns int 0/1 or -1.

Check -Wall -Wextra -Werror cleanliness: no unused params, no sign-compare issues. Comparisons like `w >= nwords` both size_t. `bv->nbits % 64u` — size_t % unsigned int → fine. `(1ull << (bv->nbits % 64u))` — shift count is size_t, fine.

In `range_mask(unsigned lo, unsigned hi)` — parameters unsigned int; call sites cast. For set_range: `lo % 64` is size_t in [0,63], cast to unsigned — fine.

One more check on the "change nothing on invalid range" requirement: validate before any writes. Yes, public functions validate first.

bv_init must also handle NULL bv. `bv_init(NULL, words, 10)` → -1. Check order: `if (bv == NULL || words == NULL || nbits == 0) return -1;`.

Zero the words with a loop (no string.h allowed — only stdint/stddef). Loop:
```c
for (size_t w = 0; w < BV_WORDS(nbits); w++) words[w] = 0;
```

Now write the files.

Also note test `next_clear_in_a_dense_map`: nbits=130, set_range(0,130) — all 130 valid bits set, tail of last word (word 2, bits 130..191, i.e., 62 bits) must remain clear. bv_next_clear(0) must return -1 — our valid-mask handles this (word 2: valid = (1<<2)-1 = 0b11, ~words[2] has all upper bits set but masked out; bits 0..1 set so ~words[2]&valid = 0). Then skip → w=3 >= nwords=3 → -1. 

`tail_word_discipline`: nbits=70, BV_WORDS(70)=2. set_range(0,70): w0=0, w1=(69)/64=1, startbit=0, endbit=69%64+1=5+1=6. w0 != w1: words[0] |= mask(0,64) = ~0; words[1] |= mask(0,6) = 0x3F. count = 64+6 = 70. clear_range(64,70): w0=1, w1=1, startbit=0, endbit=(69%64)+1=6, mask=0x3F → words[1] &= ~0x3F → 0. count=64. next_set(64): w=1, cur = words[1] & (~0<<0) = 0 → ++w=2 >= 2 → -1. flip(69): words[1] ^= 1<<5. count=65. next_set(64) → 64+5=69. 

Test `empty_and_bad_ranges`: set_range(5,5) → 0 no-op: validation lo<=hi<=nbits: 5<=5<=192 OK, lo==hi → return 0. set_range(10,300): hi=300 > 192 → -1, no change. set_range(20,10): lo>hi → -1. count_range(10,5) → -1, count_range(0,193) → -1.

Note: BV_WORDS(nbits) with nbits=130 → (130+63)/64 = 193/64 = 3 words. Tests use arrays of 4, fine.

Let me also double check `bv_count_range` for `(hi - 1)` when lo==hi — we early-return 0 before computing hi-1. And validation ensures hi >= lo >= 0, and hi >= 1 in the non-empty path. lo,hi are size_t; hi-1 with hi>=1 fine.

Test `count_range_hits_partial_words`: count_range(0,0) → 0 via early return. count_range(191,192): w0=w1=191/64=2, startbit=191%64=63, endbit=(191%64)+1=64 → mask(63,64) = 1<<63. words[2] bit 63 = bit 191. Good.

Now, the header needs to exactly match the given surface, including the BV_WORDS macro. Write both files, run make test.

Also, make sure there are no warnings with -Wall -Wextra -Werror: 
- unused-parameter: none.
- `for (size_t w = ...)` C17 fine.
- Comparison of integer expressions of different signedness: `w * 64u + ctz64(cur)` — size_t + unsigned → size_t; cast to long — implementation-defined if huge, fine.

One more consideration: in bv_next_set I compute nwords via BV_WORDS(bv->nbits). The macro multiplies out fine.

Let me write the code.

bitvec.h:

```c
/* bitvec.h — bitmap over caller-owned 64-bit word storage.
 *
 * Tracks nbits bits in BV_WORDS(nbits) caller-supplied words; the library
 * never allocates and only ever touches those words. Bit 0 is the least
 * significant bit of words[0], bit 64 the LSB of words[1], and so on.
 * Bits past nbits in the final word are never set by any operation.
 *
 * Ranges are half-open [lo, hi) with strict bounds: lo <= hi <= nbits or
 * the call fails with -1 and changes nothing (never clamps). lo == hi is
 * a valid no-op.
 */
#ifndef BITVEC_H
#define BITVEC_H

#include <stdint.h>
#include <stddef.h>

#define BV_WORDS(nbits) (((nbits) + 63u) / 64u)

typedef struct {
    uint64_t *words;   /* caller storage, BV_WORDS(nbits) elements */
    size_t    nbits;
} bitvec;

int    bv_init(bitvec *bv, uint64_t *words, size_t nbits);
int    bv_set(bitvec *bv, size_t i);
int    bv_clear(bitvec *bv, size_t i);
int    bv_flip(bitvec *bv, size_t i);
int    bv_test(const bitvec *bv, size_t i);
int    bv_set_range(bitvec *bv, size_t lo, size_t hi);
int    bv_clear_range(bitvec *bv, size_t lo, size_t hi);
size_t bv_count(const bitvec *bv);
long   bv_count_range(const bitvec *bv, size_t lo, size_t hi);
long   bv_next_set(const bitvec *bv, size_t from);
long   bv_next_clear(const bitvec *bv, size_t from);

#endif /* BITVEC_H */
```

bitvec.c — as designed. Let me make sure helpers are static and there's no global state (static functions are fine — "no globals, no statics" means no mutable static state; static helper functions are normal C. To be extra safe I could avoid the `static` keyword... no, that would export symbols; static functions are standard and don't violate "no statics" which is about state. Keep static functions.)

Write it:

```c
#include "bitvec.h"

/* bits [lo, hi) within one 64-bit word; 0 <= lo <= hi <= 64 */
static uint64_t word_range_mask(unsigned lo, unsigned hi)
{
    uint64_t below_hi = (hi == 64u) ? ~0ull : ((1ull << hi) - 1ull);
    return below_hi & (~0ull << lo);
}

static size_t popcount64(uint64_t x)
{
    x = x - ((x >> 1) & 0x5555555555555555ull);
    x = (x & 0x3333333333333333ull) + ((x >> 2) & 0x3333333333333333ull);
    x = (x + (x >> 4)) & 0x0F0F0F0F0F0F0F0Full;
    return (size_t)((x * 0x0101010101010101ull) >> 56);
}

/* index of the lowest set bit; x must be nonzero */
static unsigned lowest_bit(uint64_t x)
{
    return (unsigned)popcount64((x & (~x + 1ull)) - 1ull);
}
```

Hmm, `lowest_bit` via popcount of (lowbit - 1): for x = 1<<63, lowbit-1 = 0x7FFF...F, popcount 63. Good.

Then init, single-bit ops, range ops, count, count_range, scanners. Let me now write everything and test.

For set_range/clear_range I'll have a shared static `range_apply(bitvec *bv, size_t lo, size_t hi, int set)` — but "no globals, no statics" — again functions are fine.

Full bitvec.c:

```c
#include "bitvec.h"

/* Mask of bits [lo, hi) inside a single 64-bit word. 0 <= lo <= hi <= 64. */
static uint64_t word_range_mask(unsigned lo, unsigned hi)
{
    uint64_t below_hi = (hi == 64u) ? ~0ull : ((1ull << hi) - 1ull);
    return below_hi & (~0ull << lo);
}

static size_t popcount64(uint64_t x)
{
    x = x - ((x >> 1) & 0x5555555555555555ull);
    x = (x & 0x3333333333333333ull) + ((x >> 2) & 0x3333333333333333ull);
    x = (x + (x >> 4)) & 0x0F0F0F0F0F0F0F0Full;
    return (size_t)((x * 0x0101010101010101ull) >> 56);
}

/* Index of the least significant set bit; x must be nonzero. */
static unsigned lowest_bit(uint64_t x)
{
    return (unsigned)popcount64((x & (~x + 1ull)) - 1ull);
}

int bv_init(bitvec *bv, uint64_t *words, size_t nbits)
{
    if (bv == NULL || words == NULL || nbits == 0)
        return -1;
    for (size_t w = 0; w < BV_WORDS(nbits); w++)
        words[w] = 0;
    bv->words = words;
    bv->nbits = nbits;
    return 0;
}

int bv_set(bitvec *bv, size_t i)
{
    if (i >= bv->nbits)
        return -1;
    bv->words[i / 64] |= 1ull << (i % 64);
    return 0;
}

int bv_clear(bitvec *bv, size_t i)
{
    if (i >= bv->nbits)
        return -1;
    bv->words[i / 64] &= ~(1ull << (i % 64));
    return 0;
}

int bv_flip(bitvec *bv, size_t i)
{
    if (i >= bv->nbits)
        return -1;
    bv->words[i / 64] ^= 1ull << (i % 64);
    return 0;
}

int bv_test(const bitvec *bv, size_t i)
{
    if (i >= bv->nbits)
        return -1;
    return (bv->words[i / 64] >> (i % 64)) & 1ull;
}
```

Careful: `(bv->words[i / 64] >> (i % 64)) & 1ull` is uint64_t; returning int — implicit conversion, value 0/1, fine. -Wextra doesn't warn on that conversion (no -Wconversion). Good.

```c
/* Apply set (set != 0) or clear (set == 0) to [lo, hi); caller validated. */
static void range_apply(bitvec *bv, size_t lo, size_t hi, int set)
{
    size_t w0 = lo / 64;
    size_t w1 = (hi - 1) / 64;
    unsigned startbit = (unsigned)(lo % 64);
    unsigned endbit = (unsigned)((hi - 1) % 64) + 1u;

    if (w0 == w1) {
        uint64_t m = word_range_mask(startbit, endbit);
        if (set)
            bv->words[w0] |= m;
        else
            bv->words[w0] &= ~m;
        return;
    }
    if (set) {
        bv->words[w0] |= word_range_mask(startbit, 64u);
        for (size_t w = w0 + 1; w < w1; w++)
            bv->words[w] = ~0ull;
        bv->words[w1] |= word_range_mask(0u, endbit);
    } else {
        bv->words[w0] &= ~word_range_mask(startbit, 64u);
        for (size_t w = w0 + 1; w < w1; w++)
            bv->words[w] = 0;
        bv->words[w1] &= ~word_range_mask(0u, endbit);
    }
}

static int range_valid(const bitvec *bv, size_t lo, size_t hi)
{
    return lo <= hi && hi <= bv->nbits;
}

int bv_set_range(bitvec *bv, size_t lo, size_t hi)
{
    if (!range_valid(bv, lo, hi))
        return -1;
    if (lo < hi)
        range_apply(bv, lo, hi, 1);
    return 0;
}

int bv_clear_range(bitvec *bv, size_t lo, size_t hi)
{
    if (!range_valid(bv, lo, hi))
        return -1;
    if (lo < hi)
        range_apply(bv, lo, hi, 0);
    return 0;
}

size_t bv_count(const bitvec *bv)
{
    size_t total = 0;
    for (size_t w = 0; w < BV_WORDS(bv->nbits); w++)
        total += popcount64(bv->words[w]);
    return total;
}

long bv_count_range(const bitvec *bv, size_t lo, size_t hi)
{
    if (!range_valid(bv, lo, hi))
        return -1;
    if (lo == hi)
        return 0;

    size_t w0 = lo / 64;
    size_t w1 = (hi - 1) / 64;
    unsigned startbit = (unsigned)(lo % 64);
    unsigned endbit = (unsigned)((hi - 1) % 64) + 1u;
    size_t total;

    if (w0 == w1) {
        total = popcount64(bv->words[w0] & word_range_mask(startbit, endbit));
    } else {
        total = popcount64(bv->words[w0] & word_range_mask(startbit, 64u));
        for (size_t w = w0 + 1; w < w1; w++)
            total += popcount64(bv->words[w]);
        total += popcount64(bv->words[w1] & word_range_mask(0u, endbit));
    }
    return (long)total;
}

long bv_next_set(const bitvec *bv, size_t from)
{
    if (from >= bv->nbits)
        return -1;

    size_t nwords = BV_WORDS(bv->nbits);
    size_t w = from / 64;
    uint64_t cur = bv->words[w] & (~0ull << (from % 64));

    for (;;) {
        if (cur != 0)
            return (long)(w * 64 + (size_t)lowest_bit(cur));
        if (++w >= nwords)
            return -1;
        cur = bv->words[w];
    }
}

long bv_next_clear(const bitvec *bv, size_t from)
{
    if (from >= bv->nbits)
        return -1;

    size_t nwords = BV_WORDS(bv->nbits);
    size_t w = from / 64;
    uint64_t cur = ~bv->words[w] & (~0ull << (from % 64));

    for (;;) {
        if (w == nwords - 1 && (bv->nbits % 64) != 0)
            cur &= (1ull << (bv->nbits % 64)) - 1ull;
        if (cur != 0)
            return (long)(w * 64 + (size_t)lowest_bit(cur));
        if (++w >= nwords)
            return -1;
        cur = ~bv->words[w];
    }
}
