    typedef struct { uint64_t red; uint64_t yel; int moves; } c4;

    void    c4_init(c4 *p);
    int     c4_drop(c4 *p, int col);
    int     c4_encode(c4 *p, const char *moves);
    int     c4_win(uint64_t bb);
    uint8_t c4_legal(const c4 *p);
    long    c4_perft(const c4 *p, int depth);

Board layout is fixed and the tests peek at raw bitboards, so follow it bit for bit: standard 7 columns x 6 rows; bit index = col*7 + row with row 0 at the BOTTOM; bit col*7 + 6 is a sentinel row that stays empty forever (that gap is what makes shift tricks safe). Red always moves first; moves counts total stones, so red is to move exactly when moves is even.

- c4_init: both boards empty, moves 0.
- c4_drop(col): the side to move drops a stone in col; it lands on the lowest empty row. Returns -1 without changing anything when col is outside 0..6, the column already holds six stones, or the game is over (either side has four in a row, or all 42 cells are filled). Returns 0 on success.
- c4_encode: reset to the empty position, then replay a NUL-terminated move string one digit per move, '0'..'6' = the column. Any bad character or illegal drop (including a move after the game ended) returns -1; a clean replay returns 0. NULL string is -1.
