Scoring, the way the rulebook means it:

- Fifteens: 2 points for every distinct combination of two or more of the five cards whose values sum to exactly 15. Ace counts 1, face cards count 10, everything else pip value. Combinations are distinct by card identity, not by rank — three fives and a ten is three different fifteens.
- Pairs: 2 points per pair of same-rank cards. Three of a kind is three pairs (6), four of a kind is six pairs (12). Rank means rank — a jack and a ten are not a pair.
- Runs: only the longest run counts. Find the longest stretch of consecutive ranks (length 3 or more) present among the five cards; score its length multiplied by the product of the rank multiplicities in it. So 4-5-6-6 is a double run worth 6, 7-7-7-8-9 is a triple run worth 9, 8-8-9-9-T scores 12, and a run of four never also scores its inner runs of three. Ace is low only: A-2-3 runs, Q-K-A does not.
- Flush: for a regular hand, four hand cards of one suit score 4, and 5 if the starter matches too. For the crib (is_crib true) a four-card flush is worth nothing — only all five of one suit scores, and that scores 5.
- His nobs: 1 point for holding the jack of the starter's suit in the hand. A jack turned up as the starter earns nothing from this function.
- total is the sum of the five parts.

