messages.content:
=== MOONSHINER TASK BOUNDARY ===

Our aquarium-monitoring dashboard passes snapshots of sensor readings around as const std::vector / std::list, and every panel carves out a subset: flagged probes, one tank's sensors, values over a threshold. Today each panel runs std::copy_if into a scratch vector, which copies readings for no reason. std::ranges::views::filter looked like the obvious answer, but it caches begin() and is not const-iterable, and our panel plumbing hands views around by const reference — so we want our own tiny, boring filter view.

Create filterview.hpp (header-only, C++20, standard library only; the existing Makefile builds test_filterview.cpp against it) with exactly this interface:

    template <class It, class Pred>
    class FilterView {
    public:
        class iterator;                           // contract below
        FilterView(It first, It last, Pred pred); // half-open [first, last)
        iterator begin() const;  // at the first matching element
        iterator end() const;    // past-the-end sentinel position
        bool empty() const;      // true iff no element matches
    };

    template <class C, class Pred>
    FilterView<typename C::const_iterator, Pred> filtered(const C &c, Pred pred);

Contract:
- The view never copies, moves or modifies source elements and never allocates; operator* on the iterator returns a reference to the original element sitting in the source container.
- iterator member types: iterator_category = std::forward_iterator_tag, value_type = std::iterator_traits<It>::value_type, difference_type = std::ptrdiff_t, and reference/pointer taken from std::iterator_traits<It>. operator-> must work.
- iterator must model the C++20 std::forward_iterator concept — the tests static_assert this — so it is default-constructible, copyable, equality-comparable and multi-pass. Two default-constructed iterators compare equal. Copies advance independently: after `auto b = a; ++b;` the iterator a still reads the old element.
- begin() skips leading non-matching elements; ++ always lands on the next matching element or on end(); post-increment returns the position before the step; if nothing matches, begin() == end().
- begin()/end()/empty() are const and callable any number of times — iterating a view is repeatable and never consumes it (this is exactly where ranges::filter_view fought us).
- It can be any forward source iterator: std::vector<T>::const_iterator and std::list<T>::const_iterator both work, over full ranges or subranges, and plain class template argument deduction from the three-argument constructor must work: FilterView view(v.begin(), v.end(), pred);
- Pred is any pure predicate callable as pred(*it) — function pointer or lambda. The view may call it as often as it likes (each pass re-tests every element it walks over), so predicates with side effects are out of scope.
- filtered(container, pred) is a convenience wrapper over the container's full const range; a range-for directly over its result must work: for (const Reading &r : filtered(readings, is_flagged)) { ... }

Worked example:

    std::vector<int> temps = {74, 81, 76, 90};
    auto hot = filtered(temps, [](const int &t) { return t >= 80; });
    // range-for over hot visits 81 then 90; hot.empty() is false;
    // std::distance(hot.begin(), hot.end()) == 2

`make test` must pass (test_filterview.cpp, mintest.h and the Makefile are fixed); the tests also run std::distance, std::accumulate and std::find_if over the view's iterators.

