messages.content:
=== MOONSHINER TASK BOUNDARY ===

Our board-game club wants a gomoku referee with a practice opponent, and I want the rules engine done properly this time — the last attempt called a six-in-a-row a win and the club's rules lawyer had a field day. C++20, stdlib only, two files: gomoku.h and gomoku.cpp. The header must expose exactly this:

    struct Gomoku { /* your representation, default-constructible */ };

    void gm_init(Gomoku *g);
    int  gm_at(const Gomoku *g, int r, int c);
    int  gm_to_move(const Gomoku *g);
    int  gm_winner(const Gomoku *g);
    bool gm_play(Gomoku *g, int r, int c);
    int  gm_replay(Gomoku *g, const std::string &moves);
    bool gm_bot(const Gomoku *g, int *r, int *c);

Board is 15x15, rows and cols 0..14. Black is 1 and moves first, white is 2. gm_at returns 0/1/2 for a cell, -1 out of range. gm_play places a stone for the side to move and returns false — changing nothing — when the cell is out of range or occupied, or the game is already decided. gm_winner: 0 while play continues, 1 or 2 for a winner, 3 when all 225 cells are filled with no winner.

The win rule is EXACT five: a move wins if and only if, in one of the four line directions, the maximal contiguous run of the mover's stones through the new stone is exactly five. Six or more is an overline — worth nothing, the game just continues. A single move can make an overline one way and an exact five another way; the five still wins.

gm_replay resets to a fresh board, then applies moves from a space-separated string of "r,c" tokens. It returns -1 if every move was legal, otherwise the 0-based index of the first rejected move — leaving the legal prefix on the board.

gm_bot suggests a move for the side to move (never modifies the game; returns false only when no move exists or the game is over). It works down five tiers, taking the FIRST hit in row-major scan order ((0,0),(0,1),...,(14,14)) within each tier before falling to the next:

1. win now: placing our stone there wins under the exact-five rule.
2. block win: the opponent placing there would win under the exact-five rule. Careful: a gap whose filling would make the opponent an overline is NOT a threat and must not be "blocked".
3. make four: our stone there leaves a maximal run of exactly four of ours in some direction.
4. block four: the opponent's stone there would leave them a maximal run of exactly four.
5. center-most: the empty cell with the smallest Chebyshev distance to (7,7), ties broken row-major.

test_gomoku.cpp is the contract — full-game transcripts (including a 225-move draw), the overline laws from both sides, and one pinned bot answer per tier. make test gates it; test_gomoku.cpp, mintest.h and the Makefile stay as they are.

