       // for T; a T object is constructed in place (std::construct_at) only
       // when an element is pushed and is destroyed individually
       // (std::destroy_at) when popped, cleared or overwritten.  No heap.
       //
       // Why two arenas: copy assignment must be all-or-nothing for every
       // permitted T (copy/move constructible + destructible only, moves may
       // throw).  With a single arena the new elements would have to be
       // constructed in slots still occupied by the old ones, so a throwing
       // element constructor could leave the target gutted.  Staging the new
       // contents in the idle arena and only then retiring the old ones makes
       // the operation atomic.  (Copy-and-swap is not an option either:
       // committing would need element moves, which are allowed to throw.)
       alignas(T) std::byte arena_[2][N * sizeof(T)];

