```csharp
/// <summary>
/// The publishing calendar on logical day numbers: one issue every 7 days
/// starting at the first publish day. No wall-clock types anywhere.
/// </summary>
public class IssueCalendar
{
    private const int PeriodDays = 7;

    public IssueCalendar(int firstPublishDay)
    {
        if (firstPublishDay < 0)
            throw new ArgumentException("first publish day must be non-negative");
        FirstPublishDay = firstPublishDay;
    }

    public int FirstPublishDay { get; }

    public int PublishDay(int issueNumber)
    {
        if (issueNumber < 1)
            throw new ArgumentException("issue numbers start at 1");
        return FirstPublishDay + (issueNumber - 1) * PeriodDays;
    }

    public int NextIssueOnOrAfter(int day)
    {
        if (day <= FirstPublishDay)
            return 1;
        int elapsed = day - FirstPublishDay; // > 0
        int weeksAfterFirst = (elapsed + PeriodDays - 1) / PeriodDays; // ceil
        return weeksAfterFirst + 1;
    }

    public bool IsPublishDay(int day)
    {
        return day >= FirstPublishDay && (day - FirstPublishDay) % PeriodDays == 0;
    }

    public int IssueOn(int day)
    {
        if (!IsPublishDay(day))
            throw new ArgumentException($"day {day} is not a publish day");
        return (day - FirstPublishDay) / PeriodDays + 1;
    }
}
```

The interpolated `$"day {day}..."` uses current culture for the int; ints format identically in practice but negative sign for negative days... day could be negative, e.g. IssueOn(-5)? "day -5 is not a publish day". InvariantCulture for safety. Since the message must round-trip verbatim, and CurrentCulture could theoretically alter digits (some cultures use non-ASCII digits for ToString()? Actually .NET numeric formatting always uses ASCII digits for standard formats; negative sign comes from culture's NumberFormatInfo.NegativeSign which could differ in theory). To be safe, format messages with invariant culture too. The tests run under default culture, so it would pass either way, but the determinism law says formatting must not vary with machine locale. I'll use string.Create(CultureInfo.InvariantCulture, ...) for messages containing numbers, or FormattableString.Invariant. 

