Implementation plan:

```csharp
namespace Microfiche;

public sealed record FrameRecord(string FrameId, string Reel);

public interface IReelStore
{
    IReadOnlyList<FrameRecord> ScanBatch(int offset, int pageSize);
}

public static class ReelScanner
{
    public static IEnumerable<FrameRecord> Stream(IReelStore store, int pageSize)
    {
        ArgumentNullException.ThrowIfNull(store);
        ArgumentOutOfRangeException.ThrowIfLessThan(pageSize, 1);
        return StreamCore(store, pageSize);
    }

    private static IEnumerable<FrameRecord> StreamCore(IReelStore store, int pageSize)
    {
        var offset = 0;
        while (true)
        {
            var batch = store.ScanBatch(offset, pageSize);
            foreach (var frame in batch)
                yield return frame;
            if (batch.Count < pageSize)
                yield break;
            offset += batch.Count; // or offset += pageSize
        }
    }

    public static IEnumerable<IReadOnlyList<FrameRecord>> Pages(IReelStore store, int pageSize)
    {
        ArgumentNullException.ThrowIfNull(store);
        ArgumentOutOfRangeException.ThrowIfLessThan(pageSize, 1);
        return PagesCore(store, pageSize);
    }

    private static IEnumerable<IReadOnlyList<FrameRecord>> PagesCore(IReelStore store, int pageSize)
    {
        var offset = 0;
        while (true)
        {
            var batch = store.ScanBatch(offset, pageSize);
            if (batch.Count == 0)
                yield break;
            yield return batch;
            if (batch.Count < pageSize)
                yield break;
            offset += batch.Count;
        }
    }

    public static FrameRecord? FirstMatch(IReelStore store, int pageSize, Func<FrameRecord, bool> predicate)
    {
        ArgumentNullException.ThrowIfNull(store);
        ArgumentNullException.ThrowIfNull(predicate);
        ArgumentOutOfRangeException.ThrowIfLessThan(pageSize, 1);
        var offset = 0;
        while (true)
        {
            var batch = store.ScanBatch(offset, pageSize);
            foreach (var frame in batch)
            {
                if (predicate(frame))
                    return frame;
            }
            if (batch.Count < pageSize)
                return null;
            offset += batch.Count;
        }
    }
}
```

Wait — one nuance on offset advancement. The contract says `ScanBatch(int offset, int pageSize)` returns up to pageSize frames beginning at 0-based offset. When a batch returns exactly pageSize frames, we request the next batch at offset + pageSize. The tests expect offsets (0,10),(10,10),(20,10) — so offset += pageSize or offset += batch.Count are equivalent when batch.Count == pageSize. I'll use `offset += pageSize` since we only continue when the batch is full. Actually `offset += batch.Count` is also fine since we only continue when count == pageSize. Either works. I'll use pageSize for clarity.

For Pages: should the empty final scan for an exact-multiple archive yield an empty page? Test says full walk on 24 yields [10,10,4] — short tail ends. For exact multiple (20), pages would be [10,10] then a scan at (20,10) returns empty, stop — do we yield the empty page? The spec says "the tail batch comes through short, never padded up" — empty batch should not be yielded, I think. The test for exact multiple only exists for Stream. For Pages, yielding an empty list would be weird. My implementation: if batch.Count == 0, yield break before yielding. That handles the empty archive (first batch empty → no pages at all) and exact-multiple (final empty scan → not yielded). That seems right.

Edge: for Stream, empty batch handling — the foreach yields nothing, then batch.Count (0) < pageSize → yield break. Fine, no special case needed.

Note the test `Assert.Equal(new[] { (0, 10) }, store.Scans)` — comparing `List<(int Offset, int PageSize)>` with an array of `(int, int)`. xUnit's Assert.Equal with IEnumerable<T> works since tuples with different names are the same type. Fine.

Also `ArgumentOutOfRangeException.ThrowIfLessThan(pageSize, 1)` — available since .NET 7/8. .NET 10, fine.

The validation test asserts `store.Scans` is empty after the throws — validation happens before any scan. Good.

